hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a magnetized plasma in a toroidal confinement device where a mean electric field-cross-magnetic field ($\mathbf{E}\times\mathbf{B}$) flow with constant radial shear rate $S$ advects microturbulent eddies. In quasilinear theory, take the ion heat flux to be $Q \sim \sum_{\mathbf{k}} k_y\,\operatorname{Im}\!\left(\tilde{T}_{\mathbf{k}}\,\tilde{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}^{*}\right)$, where $\tilde{T}_{\mathbf{k}}$ and $\tilde{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}$ are the Fourier components of the temperature and electrostatic potential fluctuations at perpendicular wavevector $\mathbf{k}=(k_x,k_y)$. Assume a linear response $\tilde{T}_{\mathbf{k}}=\hat{\chi}(\mathbf{k})\,\tilde{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}$ with a complex coefficient $\hat{\chi}(\mathbf{k})$ set by the underlying drift-wave physics, so that $Q$ reduces to a spectrum weighted by $|\tilde{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}|^{2}$.

Starting from:
- Advection by the mean shear flow, modeled as $\mathbf{V}_E(x)=S\,x\,\hat{\mathbf{y}}$, and the consequent shearing-wave evolution of the wavevector $k_x(t)=k_x(0)+k_ySt$;
- A local Taylor expansion of the linear growth rate near its maximum at fixed $k_y$ of interest, $\gamma(\mathbf{k})\approx\gamma_0 - D\,k_{\perp}^{2}$ with $k_{\perp}^{2}=k_x^{2}+k_y^{2}$ and constants $\gamma_0>0$, $D>0$;

derive how the shear modifies the time dependence of the fluctuation spectrum $|\tilde{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}(t)|^{2}$ for a packet initialized at $k_x(0)=0$, and use this to obtain the scaling of the quasilinear heat diffusivity $\chi$ with the shear rate $S$. Here, define the diffusivity $\chi$ through $Q=-n\,\chi\,\nabla T$, with $n$ and $\nabla T$ treated as constant background quantities so that they do not introduce any dependence on $S$ into the scaling. You may assume that the relevant contribution to $Q$ for a given $k_y$ is given by a time integral over the packet lifetime of $k_y\,\operatorname{Im}\!\left(\hat{\chi}(\mathbf{k})\right)\,|\tilde{\phi}_{\mathbf{k}}(t)|^{2}$ with $k_x(t)=k_y S t$.

Report the exponent $\alpha$ defined by the strong-shear scaling $\chi\propto S^{-\alpha}$. Your final answer must be a single real number. No rounding is required, and no units are needed for $\alpha$ since it is dimensionless.
